                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>THE ANNALS OF HYGIENE.<lb/>
                UNIVERSITY OF PENNSYLVANIA PRESS&#44;<lb/>
                716 FILBERT ST.&#44; PHILADELPHIA&#44;<lb/>
                PUBLISHERS.<lb/></p>
            <p>JOSEPH F. EDWARDS&#44; A.M.&#44; M.D.&#44;<lb/>		
                Editor.<lb/></p>						
                <p>OFFICE OF THE EDITOR.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">1625 Pacific Avenue</hi>.<lb/>
                    Atlantic City&#44; N. J.&#44; June 23&#34; 1897.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev&#58; S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>In a letter recently<lb/> received by me from the venerable and<lb/> distinguished Dr&#58; Alfred Still&#233;&#44; of<lb/> Philadelphia&#44; the following paragraph<lb/> appears&#59; &#34;If other nations had adopted<lb/> the Sanitary laws of the Jews there<lb/> would be much less need than now<lb/> for physicians&#34;.  I am&#44; myself&#44; most<lb/> heartily in accord with this sentiment.<lb/>  I have thought that it would prove of<lb/> great benefit to mankind at large<lb/> to know something about the Sanitary<lb/> laws of the Jews&#44; hence I appeal to you&#44;<lb/> as the most profound Hebrew scholar<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>in this country&#44; to ask if you<lb/> will not kindly prepare me a<lb/> short article on this subject for<lb/> &#34;The Annals of Hygiene&#34;<lb/> Very Truly Yours<lb/> Joseph. F. Edwards<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
